author: @trevorbuchanan5962
text: `save` is deprecated in favor of `push`. and push is implicit. It's slightly different in that `save` would concatenate all non-option arguments and make those the message. `push` can take non-option arguments, and so requires `-m '<message>'` just like `commit`. In other words, `git stash -m 'message'` is the same as `git stash save message`  man pages are fun!

author: @mikefdorst
text: You don't need to use the full name `stash@{0}`, you can just use `0`. Also, note that the `save "message"` part is unneeded too. Since stashes are generally a quick cleanup solution so you can do a git operation, they don't usually live long and I can usually remember what they are without a name.
